This case has not been concluded. Unless a judgment of conviction is entered, the defendant is presumed innocent of all charges.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Preliminary hearing on September 13, 2022 at 10:00 am.

10:00 AM Defendant Tucker Mickail Cady in Court.  Attorney Aaron A. Nelson in Court for Tucker Mickail Cady.  ADA Joseph M. Schieffer in Court for State of Wisconsin.  S/T RF Sgt. Scott Bangert.  Direct by ADA Schieffer.  Defendant identified.  Cross by Atty. Nelson.  Officer excused.  State rests.  Atty. Nelson declines witnesses and argument.  State requests Court find probable cause and bind defendant over.  Court makes findings; finds probable cause and binds defendant over.  Atty. Nelson requests Arraignment set out.  Court directs Defendant to report to the Jail for fingerprints and photographs within 10 days.  Atty. Nelson advises that he did so this morning.  Advises of intent to file 971.20 motion.  Court confirms defendant's address and phone.  Atty. Nelson requests to note for the record that he did not refuse a copy of the bond but digitally provided one to his client.  Arraignment scheduled for September 22, 2022 at 09:00 am.
